  <section id="stuff">
    <p><b>faic</b> is an <a href="../../xx/irregularVerbs.php">irregular verb</a> of visual
      perception corresponding to the English ‘see’. It is closely related to the other visual verbs
          <b><a href="seall.php">seall</a></b> ‘look’, ‘show’, <b><a href="coimhead.php"
          >coimhead</a></b> ‘look’, <b><a href="mothaich.php">mothaich</a></b> ‘notice’, and the
      idiom <b><a href="../nouns/suuil.php#thoir_suuil_air">thoir sùil (air)</a></b> ‘look (at)’. It
      is also closely related to the verb of auditory perception <b><a href="cluinn.php"
        >cluinn</a></b> ‘hear’.</p>

    <p>The main uses of <b>faic</b> are: <ul>
        <li>transitive <ul>
            <li><a href="#strict_transitive">strict transitive</a> e.g. <em>faic duine</em></li>
            <li><a href="#object_control">with an object-controlled predicate</a> e.g. <em>faic
                duine a’ dèanamh rud</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>pseudo-transitive <ul>
            <li><a href="#declarative_clause">with a declarative clause</a> e.g. <em>faic gu bheil /
                nach eil ...</em></li>
            <li><a href="#question">with a (constituent) question</a> e.g. <em>faic dè a tha
                ...</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <hr/>
    <h id="transitive">Transitive uses</h>
    <p><b>faic</b> is usually used as a transitive verb, with an explicit direct object noun phrase
      denoting the person or object visually perceived (or otherwise encountered).</p>
    <h5 id="strict_transitive">Strict transitive</h5>
    <p>The most basic use of <b>faic</b> is as a <em>strict</em> transitive verb, with just the
      direct object and no other arguments.</p>

    <p>cf. <b><a href="mothaich.php#do">mothaich do rud</a></b> ‘notice something’.</p>
    <h5 id="object_control">With object-controlled predicate</h5>
    <p>Transitive <b>faic</b> can also govern a predicate phrase describing some aspect of the
      direct object. For example, this predicate can be a prepositional phrase denoting the
        <em>location</em> of the object:</p>

    <p>The predicate can also be a progressive phrase with a verbal noun governed by the particle
        <b>ag</b>:</p>

